query: How does the garbage collection mechanism work in Java?
question: How does the garbage collection mechanism work in Java?
Answer: The Garbage Collection (GC) is a process of reclaiming memory from objects that are no longer referenced by any active object. In other words, it removes unused objects and makes their memory available for new objects to be created. The GC is an automatic process which runs periodically in the background without affecting the running program. It works on the principle of mark-and-sweep algorithm wherein all live objects are marked as “live” while all dead objects are swept away. This ensures efficient use of resources and prevents unnecessary waste of time during runtime execution. Additionally, this also helps reduce memory usage since only those parts of code which need to remain alive will continue to exist after each cycle has completed its task
